<!-- ============= Introduction =====-->
  <sect1 id="menubar-introduction"> 
	 <title>Introduction</title> 
     
<!-- ==== Figure ==================-->
	 <figure id="menubar-startup"> 
		<title>&applet; Applet</title> 
		<screenshot> 
		  <mediaobject> 
			 <imageobject><imagedata fileref="figures/menubar.png" format="PNG"/>
				
			 </imageobject> 
			 <textobject> 
				<phrase>Screenshot of the &applet; applet. Shows Applications menu,
				  Actions menu, Preferences menu Windows menu, and Workspaces menu.</phrase> 
			 </textobject> 
		  </mediaobject> 
		</screenshot> 
	 </figure> 
	 <para>
		The <application>&applet;</application> applet provides a customizable
		menubar that you can put into any panel on the desktop. To add
		<application>&applet;</application> to a panel, right-click on the panel to
		open the 
		<guimenu>Panel</guimenu> menu, then choose 
		<menuchoice> 
		  <guimenu>Add to Panel</guimenu> 
		  <guisubmenu>Utility</guisubmenu> 
		  <guimenuitem>Menu Bar</guimenuitem> 
		</menuchoice>. 
	 </para>
	 <para>
		The <application>&applet;</application> applet provides you with the
		following menus: 
		<variablelist> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>Standard menus</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<para>
				  Five standard menus provide you with access to all of the desktop
				  functionality. The features of the standard menus are as follows: 
				  <itemizedlist> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  You can remove, then subsequently re-add standard menus. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  You can not configure the contents of the standard menus. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  The standard menus always contain the same menu items. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  The menu items in the standard menus always provide the
						  same functionality. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
				  </itemizedlist> 
				</para>
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>Configurable menus</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<para>
				  Four types of configurable menus enable you to construct your own
				  menus for access to your favorite applications, shortcuts and documents. The
				  features of the configurable menus are as follows: 
				  <itemizedlist> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  Each type of configurable menu contains a different class
						  of menu item. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  You can configure the properties of each configurable menu.
						  
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  You can add as many menu items as you want to each
						  configurable menu. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  You can have as many configurable menus as you want in the
						  <application>&applet;</application> applet 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  You can change the name of the configurable menu. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
				  </itemizedlist> 
				</para>
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		</variablelist> 
	 </para>
	 <para>
		When you first start the applet, <application>&applet;</application>
		contains only standard menus, as shown in <xref linkend="menubar-startup"/>.
		<xref linkend="menubar-configured"/> shows <application>&applet;</application>
		with standard menus and custom menus. 
	 </para>
	 <figure id="menubar-configured"> 
		<title>&applet; Applet With Custom Menus</title> 
		<screenshot> 
		  <mediaobject> 
			 <imageobject><imagedata fileref="figures/menubar-configured.png"
				format="PNG"/> 
			 </imageobject> 
			 <textobject> 
				<phrase>Screenshot of the &applet; applet. Shows Applications menu,
				  Actions menu, Preferences menu Windows menu, and Workspaces menu. Shows custom
				  menus.</phrase> 
			 </textobject> 
		  </mediaobject> 
		</screenshot> 
	 </figure> 
	 <sect2 id="menubar-standard-menus"> 
		<title>Standard Menus</title> 
		<para>
		  The standard menus in <application>&applet;</application> are as
		  follows: 
		  <variablelist> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term> 
				  <guilabel>Applications</guilabel> </term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 Contains submenus with all of the main functional programs for
					 the desktop. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term> 
				  <guilabel>Actions</guilabel> </term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 Contains launchers for the following desktop functions. 
					 <itemizedlist> 
						<listitem> 
						  <para>
							 Log out 
						  </para>
						</listitem> 
						<listitem> 
						  <para>
							 Lock screen 
						  </para>
						</listitem> 
						<listitem> 
						  <para>
							 Show desktop 
						  </para>
						</listitem> 
					 </itemizedlist> 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term> 
				  <guilabel>Preferences</guilabel> </term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 Contains submenus that you can use to access the Control Center
					 capplets. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term> 
				  <guilabel>Windows</guilabel> </term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 Contains a list of all of the open windows in the current
					 workspace. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term> 
				  <guilabel>Workspaces</guilabel> </term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 Contains a list of all of the workspaces on the desktop. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
		  </variablelist> 
		</para>
	 </sect2> 
	 <sect2 id="menubar-configurable-menus"> 
		<title>Configurable Menus</title> 
		<para>
		  The types of configurable menus in <application>&applet;</application>
		  are as follows: 
		  <variablelist> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term>Menu path</term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 You can construct your own menu of favorite applications with
					 this type of configurable menu. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term>Links</term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 You can construct your own menu of launchers with this type of
					 configurable menu. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term>Directory</term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 You can assign a directory to this type of menu, for example
					 your home directory. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
			 <varlistentry> 
				<term>Documents</term> 
				<listitem> 
				  <para>
					 You can construct a menu of links to documents with this type
					 of menu. 
				  </para>
				</listitem> 
			 </varlistentry> 
		  </variablelist> 
		</para>
	 </sect2> 
  </sect1>
<!-- ================ Usage =======-->
  <sect1 id="menubar-usage"> 
	 <title>Usage</title> 
	 <para>
		You can configure <application>&applet;</application> in the following
		ways: 
	 </para>
	 <sect2 id="menubar-add-remove-menus"> 
		<title>To Add and Remove Menus</title> 
		<variablelist> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>To Add a Configurable Menu</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<para>
				  <orderedlist> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  Right-click on the <application>&applet;</application>. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  Select 
						  <guimenuitem>Add...</guimenuitem> from the applet popup
						  menu. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  Click on the button in the 
						  <guilabel>Add...</guilabel>dialog that corresponds to the
						  menu type you want. 
						</para>
						<figure id="menubar-add-dialog"> 
						  <title>Add... Dialog</title> 
						  <screenshot> 
							 <mediaobject> 
								<imageobject><imagedata
								  fileref="figures/menubar-add-dialog.png" format="PNG"/> 
								</imageobject> 
								<textobject> 
								  <phrase>Screenshot of the Add... dialog for the
									 &applet; applet. Shows buttons for custom menus.</phrase> 
								</textobject> 
							 </mediaobject> 
						  </screenshot> 
						</figure> 
					 </listitem> 
					 <listitem> 
						<para>
						  Type in the information you require in the menu-specific
						  dialog. 
						</para>
					 </listitem> 
				  </orderedlist> 
				</para>
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>To Remove a Standard Menu From &applet;</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<orderedlist> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Right-click on <application>&applet;</application>. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Select 
						<guimenuitem>Properties</guimenuitem> from the applet popup
						menu. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Clear the check box of the menu you want to remove, then
						click 
						<guibutton>OK</guibutton>. 
					 </para>
					 <para>
						If you want to add the standard menu back to
						<application>&applet;</application>, then repeat the above steps and reselect
						the check box in the <application>&applet;</application> 
						<guilabel>Properties</guilabel> dialog. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				</orderedlist> 
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>To Remove Any Menu From &applet;</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<orderedlist> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Right-click on the menu you want to remove. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Select the menu name from the applet popup menu. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				</orderedlist> 
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		</variablelist> 
	 </sect2> 
	 <sect2 id="menubar-modify"> 
		<title>To Modify &applet;</title> 
		<variablelist> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>To Move A Menu Within &applet;</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<orderedlist> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Right-click on the menu you want to move, then select 
						<guilabel>Move</guilabel>(tbd). 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Drag the menu to the new location in the
						<application>&applet;</application>applet, then release the middle mouse
						button. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				</orderedlist> 
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>To Modify Configurable Menus</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<para>
				  For each type of configurable menu, the applet popup menu
				  contains additional options that you can use to modify specific properties of
				  the configurable menu. Right-click on the configurable menu you want to modify,
				  then select the property you want to modify. 
				</para>
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		</variablelist> 
	 </sect2> 
	 <sect2 id="menubar-move"> 
		<title>To Move or Remove the &applet; Applet</title> 
		<variablelist> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>To Move <application>&applet;</application> to Another
				Panel</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<orderedlist> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Right-click anywhere on the applet. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Select 
						<guilabel>Move</guilabel> from the applet popup menu. The
						pointer changes to a cross. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Move the pointer to the panel where you want to move the
						applet, then right-click to complete the move. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				</orderedlist> 
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		  <varlistentry> 
			 <term>To Remove <application>&applet;</application> From a
				Panel</term> 
			 <listitem> 
				<orderedlist> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Right-click anywhere on the applet. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				  <listitem> 
					 <para>
						Select 
						<guilabel>Remove From Panel</guilabel> from the applet popup
						menu. 
					 </para>
				  </listitem> 
				</orderedlist> 
			 </listitem> 
		  </varlistentry> 
		</variablelist> 
	 </sect2> 
  </sect1>
